\f0\fs24 \cf0 #Riparian spider\
Riparian spiders are among the first recipients of emerging aquatic insects and are susceptible to stressors from both aquatic and terrestrial ecosystem. A model example is the horizontal orb-web spider (Tetragnatha extensa) which derives up to 70% of its diet from aquatic sources and 30% terrestrial sources. These spiders are directly or indirectly affected by cross-ecosystem stressors such as invasive crayfish and light pollution.\
\
In another field experiment by Parkinson et al. (2020), ALAN in close proximity to freshwater can intercept lateral resource flow by concentrating the fluxes of emerging aquatic insects and terrestrial consumers around lit area.\
\
Similarly, Gerg et al. (2014) found that the effect of the amphipod Dikerogammarus villous extend beyond aquatic ecosystem by reducing the abundance of web-building spider (Tetragnatha spp.) in riparian ecosystems through altered contribution of aquatic resources to their diet. \
\
