These shift in prey composition and the resulting broadening of the spider\'92s trophic niche, driven by ALAN and signal crayfish, highlight how multiple stressors can alter resource flow across linked aquatic\'96terrestrial ecosystems.\
\
Specifically, we expect ALAN to reduce signal crayfish foraging activity (REF), which in turn increase aquatic prey availability, leading to higher aquatic prey consumption and a broader isotopic niche in riparian spiders exposed to both ALAN and crayfish.
